            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Jia Miller\u2019s life is a study in texture, form, and transformation. Raised in a quiet East Bay suburb by her Chinese mother, a masterful home cook, and her American father, an architect, Jia\u2019s childhood was a fusion of precise flavors and structural design. She spent weekends watching her mother meticulously fold dumplings and her father draft blueprints, internalizing a dual appreciation for delicate craft and bold composition. This synthesis naturally led her to the arts, and she moved to San Francisco to pursue a Master of Fine Arts in Sculpture at the California College of the Arts, specializing in large-scale metalwork.\n\nAfter graduating, Jia dove into the demanding art world. She had a few gallery shows and earned critical praise, but the financial instability was draining. To support her studio, she took a dishwashing job at a celebrated Hayes Valley restaurant, eventually moving to prep. It was a turning point. One afternoon, watching the pastry chef construct a delicate sugar cage around a mousse, Jia felt a profound sense of recognition. It was sculpture, but with the added dimensions of aroma and taste\u2014ephemeral, yet more viscerally immediate than steel.\n\nShe dedicated herself to this new medium with the same intensity she had given her art. She worked her way up through San Francisco\u2019s demanding kitchens, her sculptor\u2019s eye for balance and structure giving her an edge. Now, at 48, Jia is the Executive Pastry Chef at a prestigious arts and events venue in SoMa. Her creations are renowned for their architectural beauty and inventive flavor pairings.\n\nJia lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Mission District, a neighborhood whose vibrant, creative energy still inspires her. Her daily routine begins before dawn with a 1.8-mile bicycle ride through the waking city, a quiet ritual before the heat and pressure of the kitchen. Her social life is a tight-knit circle of other chefs, artists, and neighborhood friends. Though content, Jia dreams of one day opening her own small patisserie\u2014a space that feels more like a gallery, where each dessert is displayed as a unique, edible sculpture. It would be the final, perfect fusion of her two great passions."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe is ten, perched on a stool between two worlds. To her left, the scent of ginger and scallion as her mother\u2019s swift hands pleat dough into perfect crescent moons. To her right, the sharp smell of graphite as her father\u2019s T-square glides across a vast sheet of paper, creating clean, resolute lines. In that moment, Jia understood that love, whether in a dumpling or a building, was a matter of beautiful, deliberate structure. It became the foundation of everything she would ever create.\n\n2.\nAt 27, she remembers the raw, metallic scent of her graduate studio. Her welding torch hissed, stitching together the final seam of a massive steel sculpture. She ran a hand over its cool, sweeping curve, feeling a surge of fierce pride so powerful it almost hurt. But it was immediately followed by a wave of cold panic\u2014the weight of its unsellable ambition, the rent check she couldn't cash. That sculpture was the purest expression of her art, and the moment she realized it wasn't enough to live on.\n\n3.\nIt was a Tuesday afternoon in a noisy Hayes Valley kitchen when her life changed. Jia was 31, her hands chapped from the dish pit. Through the steam, she saw the pastry chef spin hot sugar into a delicate, amber cage over a mousse. The world went silent. It was sculpture, but it was also light, aroma, and flavor. It was temporary, meant to be destroyed and experienced. In that fragile dome, she saw not the abandonment of her art, but its most profound and delicious evolution.\n\n4.\nTen years ago, for a gala at the venue, she recreated the Golden Gate Bridge as a grand dessert structure of gingerbread and spun sugar. An elderly man, a renowned structural engineer, approached her. He didn\u2019t comment on the taste. Instead, he studied the dessert\u2019s cantilevered spans and whispered, \u201cRemarkable tensile strength.\u201d That quiet, technical praise meant more than any rave review. It affirmed that she hadn't left her father\u2019s world of architecture behind; she was simply building with different materials.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on her 4:30 a.m. bike ride through the silent Mission streets, she coasted past a for-lease sign in a small storefront window. For a few blocks, she let herself design the entire space in her mind. Not a shop, but a gallery. White walls, track lighting, and a single, perfect lemon-verbena tart on a pedestal in the center. The dream felt less like a fantasy and more like a blueprint she was slowly, patiently drafting in the quiet darkness before the day began."
